snippet.title: Andrew banks valuable rankings points in California
snippet.content: SURFING: Keely Andrew has some insurance on her world tour spot, after faring well at a significant second-tier event. The Sunshine Coaster, who hovers perilously outside the top 10 on the sport's main circuit, pushed into the top five of the Qualifying Series with a fifth placing at the Paul Mitchell Neon Supergirl Pro in California. "It's my fifth year here and I feel like this is the first year where I really know the wave just because it changes so much with the tide," Andrew said. "I've got two empty results on the ratings so it's nice to fill it with a decent number, but I just want to keep bettering myself each event whether it's the CT or QS." The top six on the second tier, not including surfers who are also in the top 10 on the world tour, will earn berths on next year's main stage. Andrew was scheduled to resume her Championship Tour campaign at the Vans US Open of Surfing in California from Monday night. It's the sixth stop on the 10-event schedule. "It's starting to click and to know that my boards are feeling good heading into the US Open is great," she said. Meanwhile, fellow Coasters and world tour hopefuls Dimity Stoyle and Isabella Nichols claimed 17th and 25th placings respectively amid 109 surfers in the QS event. Sophie McCulloch was 37th. They are 13, 16th and 45th on the QS standings. Mitch Coleborn was scheduled to compete in a prominent men's QS event in California from Monday night, in his pursuit of a world tour berth.
